4 HJR___ ENCOURAGING THE STATE OF ALABAMA TO STUDY
5 NAVIGATIONAL AIDS WITHIN THE WATERWAYS OF MOBILE BAY AND
6 SURROUNDING WATERS.
7
8 WHEREAS, the waters of Baldwin County between Mobile
9 Bay, Weeks Bay, and on to the Magnolia River are frequently
10 traveled by recreational and commercial vessels; and
11 WHEREAS, navigational aids such as buoys and markers
12 assist boaters in identifying safe channels, avoiding
13 hazards, and navigating safely; and
14 WHEREAS, boaters traveling from Mobile Bay through
15 Weeks Bay to the Magnolia River have reported that
16 navigational aids in portions of these waters, particularly
17 from the federally maintained navigation aids in Mobile Bay
18 to the Magnolia River entrance channel, are sparse or
19 nonexistent, creating potential safety concerns; and
20 WHEREAS, Baldwin County's coastal waterways support
21 significant recreational boating activity and tourism,
22 making safe navigation important for the protection of life,
23 property, and local economic activity; and
24 WHEREAS, responsibility for marine patrol enforcement
25 in Alabama waters was transferred in 2015 from the Marine
26 Patrol Division of the Alabama Department of Conservation
27 and Natural Resources to the Marine Patrol Division of the
28 Alabama State Law Enforcement Agency, and Alabama
Page 1

Alabama State Law Enforcement Agency, and Alabama
HJR279 INTRODUCED
29 regulations governing public waters have historically
30 referenced the authority of the Director of the Marine
31 Patrol Division to adopt rules relating to boating safety
32 and regulatory markers on the waters of the state; and
33 WHEREAS, the safe navigation of Alabama's coastal
34 waterways is important to the protection of life and
35 property and to the continued enjoyment and responsible use
36 of these waters by residents and visitors alike; and
37 WHEREAS, some coastal states, including Florida and
38 Texas, have utilized state-administered waterway marker
39 programs in certain areas to complement federal navigation
40 aids in waters heavily used by recreational boaters; now
41 therefore,
42 BE IT RESOLVED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA, BOTH
43 HOUSES THEREOF CONCURRING, That we hereby recognize the
44 potential public safety concern associated with the lack of
45 navigational aids in the waters between Mobile Bay, Weeks
46 Bay, and on to the Magnolia River.
47 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, That the Secretary of the
48 Alabama State Law Enforcement Agency, in coordination with
49 the Alabama Department of Conservation and Natural
50 Resources, the United States Coast Guard, the State
51 Department of Transportation, and other appropriate local or
52 regional authorities, is requested to examine navigational
53 aids within these waterways and determine which governmental
54 entity is responsible for their placement and maintenance.
55 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, That within six months of the
56 adoption of this resolution, the Secretary of the Alabama
Page 2

adoption of this resolution, the Secretary of the Alabama
HJR279 INTRODUCED
57 State Law Enforcement Agency shall provide a written report
58 to the Legislature identifying the following:
59 (1) The governmental entity responsible for the
60 placement and maintenance of navigational aids between
61 Mobile Bay, Weeks Bay, and the Magnolia River.
62 (2) Any navigational safety concerns identified in
63 the area.
64 (3) Any recommendations that may assist in promoting
65 boating safety and improved navigation within these waters,
66 including considerations relating to the adoption of boating
67 safety measures or regulatory markers.
68 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, That the findings shall be
69 transmitted to the Speaker of the House of Representatives,
70 the President Pro Tempore of the Senate, the Chair of the
71 Senate, the Veterans, Military Affairs, and Public Safety
72 Committee, the Chair of the House Ports, Waterways, and
73 Intermodal Transit Committee, and the State Representative
74 for House District 94.
